 North Georgia]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[New Orleans Baptist Theological Seminary]] {{small|([[Master of Divinity|MDiv]])}}<br>[[Atlanta's John Marshall Law School|John Marshall Law School, Atlanta]] {{small|([[Juris Doctor|JD]])}}\n|website      = {{url|dougcollins.house.gov|House website}}\n|allegiance   = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch       = {{flag|United States Air Force}}\n|serviceyears = 2002\u2013present ([[Air Force Reserve Command|reservist]])\n|rank         = [[File:US-O4 insignia.svg|18px]] [[Major (United States)|Major]]\n|unit         = [[File:94th Airlift Wing.png|14px]] [[94th Airlift Wing]]\n|battles      = [[Iraq War]]\n}}\n'''Douglas A. \"Doug\" Collins''' (born August 16, 1966) is an American politician and a [[United States House of Representatives|United States Representative]] from [[Georgia's 9th congressional district]] since 2013. Previously he was a state representative in the [[Georgia House of Representatives]], representing the 27th district which includes portions of Hall, Lumpkin and White counties. Collins also serves as a Chaplain (Major) in the U.S. Air Force Reserve. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]].\n\n==Early life, education, and early career==\nBorn in [[Gainesville, Georgia]], Collins is a graduate of [[North Hall High School]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ajc.com/news/news/local-govt-politics/collins-sworn-in-as-georgias-new-member-of-congres/nTmGr/ | title =Collins sworn in as Georgia\u2019s new member of Congress | author =Daniel Malloy | publisher =''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' | date =January 3, 2013}}</ref> He attended [[North Georgia College & State University]], where he received a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in [[Political science]] and [[Criminal law]], in 1988. He attended the [[New Orleans Baptist Theological Seminary]], receiving his [[Master of Divinity]] in 1996. Collins also earned his [[Juris Doctor]] from [[John Marshall Law School (Atlanta)|John Marshall Law School]], in 2007.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/doug-collins/1d0e1ae2-4bb7-11e2-8758-b64a2997a921_topic.html | title =Doug Collins (R-Ga.) U.S. Representative, Georgia, District 9 (Since 2013) | publisher =washingtonpost.com | date =March 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\nCollins worked as an intern for Georgia Congressman [[Ed Jenkins (U.S. politician)|Ed Jenkins]], before working as a salesman, selling hazardous material safety products to Georgia's state, and local governments.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://archive.gainesvilletimes.com/news/stories/20070107/localnews/148606.shtml | title =North Hall's Doug Collins answers 'call' to office | author =Rick Lavender | publisher =ganiesvilletimes.com | date =January 7, 2007}}</ref> From 1994 to 2005, Collins was a senior [[pastor]] at Chicopee Baptist Church, while co-owning a scrapbooking retail store with his wife, Lisa.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress-legacy/georgia-9th-house-district-20121101 | title =Georgia, 9th House District Doug Collins (R) | publisher =nationaljournal.com | date =March 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"athensgop.com\">{{cite web | url=http://www.athensgop.com/2011/11/doug-collins.html | title =Doug Collins \u2013 Candidate for the 9th Congressional District | publisher =athensgop.com | date =November 2, 2011}}</ref> Collins worked as a lawyer, and has been a managing partner at the Collins and Csider law firm since 2010.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/267759-2012-new-members-guide?start=24 | title =The Hill\u2019s 2012 New Members Guide | publisher =thehill.com | date =November 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Military service==\nIn the late 1980s, Collins served two years in the [[United States Navy]], as a [[United States Navy Chaplain Corps|Navy-Chaplain]]. After the [[9/11 terrorist attacks]], Collins joined the [[United States Air Force]] [[Air Force Reserve Command|Reserve Command]] where he presently serves as a Chaplain (Major).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/2012/11/meet-the-incoming-congressional-class-veterans.html | title =Meet the Incoming Congressional Class Veterans |author1=Cindy Huang |author2=Ellen Rolfes | publisher =''[[PBS NewsHour]]'' | date =November 12, 2012}}</ref> Enlisted in the [[94th Airlift Wing]] at the [[Dobbins Air Reserve Base]] in [[Marietta, Georgia]]; Collins was deployed to [[Balad Air Base]] for five months in 2008, during the [[Iraq War]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gainesvilletimes.com/archives/5287/ | title =Rep. Doug Collins, called to serve in Iraq, will run for re-election | author =Harris Blackwood | publisher =gainesvilletimes.com | date =May 10, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Georgia House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\nCollins served three terms in the [[Georgia House of Representatives]], representing Georgia's 27th district from 2007 to 2013.\nAfter Republican incumbent state representative Stacey Reece decided he would run for the [[Georgia State Senate]], Collins announced he would run for the vacated seat. He won both the primary and general elections unopposed.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=299760 | title =GA State House 027- R Primary | publisher =ourcampaigns.com | date =July 27, 2006}}</ref> He was unopposed for reelection in 2008 and 2010.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=464367 | title =GA State House 027 | publisher =ourcampaigns.com | date =November 6, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=666350 | title =GA State House 027 | publisher =ourcampaigns.com | date =November 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nIn 2011, Collins sponsored a plan proposed by Governor Deal to reform Georgia's [[Hope Scholarship]] program.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://blogs.ajc.com/political-insider-jim-galloway/2011/02/26/the-hope-scholarship-and-a-democratic-policy-of-engagement/ | title =The HOPE scholarship and a Democratic policy of engagement | author =Jim Galloway | publisher =''[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' | date =February 26, 2011}}</ref> The bill allowed for a 10% cut in scholarships, and raised the level of the SAT and GPA test scores, required to obtain a scholarship; saving the state $300 million.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://votesmart.org/static/billtext/33879.pdf | title =HB 326/CFSA House Bill 326 (COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE) (AM) |author1=Doug Collins |author2=David Ralston |author3=Jan Jones |author4=Larry O'Neal, Jr. |author5=Stacey Abrams | publisher =votesmart.org | date =}}</ref> Collins argued that the program would be insolvent without the cut, saying that \"If you look at it at the end of the day, Georgia still leads the way in providing hope\u2014educational hope\u2014for those wanting to go on to post-secondary education.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.npr.org/2011/04/05/135146704/georgias-hope-scholarship-dwindles-amid-cutbacks | title =Georgia's HOPE Scholarship Dwindles Amid Cutbacks | author =Katy Lohr | publisher =npr.org | date =April 5, 2011}}</ref> In 2012, he supported amending [[Constitution of Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia's Constitution]] to establish a statewide commission authorizing and expanding charter schools.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://votesmart.org/bill/14963/39222/67851/establishes-a-state-charter-school-commission#.UUCPcByTgV0 | title =HB 797 \u2013 Establishes a State Charter School Commission \u2013 Key Vote | publisher =votesmart.org | date =March 13, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/06/education/future-of-georgias-charter-schools-on-ballot.html?pagewanted=all | title =Georgia\u2019s Voters Will Decide on Future of Charter Schools | author =Motoko Rich | publisher =''[[New York Times]]'' | date =November 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nCollins supports the death penalty, voting in favor of allowing juries to use the [[death penalty]], even when there isn't a unanimous verdict, if the defendant has committed at least one \u201cstatutory aggravating circumstance.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://votesmart.org/bill/4182/13006/67851/death-penalty-rules#.UUCTqxyTgV0 | title =HCS HB 185 \u2013 Death Penalty Rules \u2013 Key Vote | publisher =votesmart.org | date =March 20, 2012}}</ref> He is against [[physician assisted suicide]], voting in favor of making it a felony for anyone who \"knowingly and willingly\" assists someone in a suicide.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://votesmart.org/bill/14873/39229/67851/prohibits-assisted-suicide#.UUCT0hyTgV0 | title =HB 1114 \u2013 Prohibits Assisted Suicide \u2013 Key Vote | publisher =votesmart.org | date =May 1, 2012}}</ref> Collins voted for the failed Pre-Abortion Ultrasound Requirement, requiring doctors to give women who are undergoing an abortion the option of a free ultrasound, or to listen to the fetal heartbeat.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://votesmart.org/bill/4513/14310/67851/pre-abortion-ultrasound-requirement#.UUB26xyTgV0 | title =HCS HB 147 \u2013 Pre-Abortion Ultrasound Requirement \u2013 Key Vote | publisher =votesmart.org | accessdate =March 30, 2007 | date =March 13, 2013}}</ref> He also voted in favor of Georgia's law to prohibit Abortions past the 20th week, being one of the most restrictive early abortion bans in the country.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://votesmart.org/bill/14727/38490/67851/prohibits-abortions-after-20-weeks#.UUBzkhyTgV0 | title =HB 954 \u2013 Prohibits Abortions after 20 Weeks \u2013 Key Vote | publisher =votesmart.org |accessdate =May 1, 2012 | date =March 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012 Collins signed a pledge sponsored by [[Americans for Prosperity]] promising to vote against any Global Warming legislation that would raise taxes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americansforprosperity.org/files/Collins_Doug.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141015203917/http://americansforprosperity.org/files/Collins_Doug.pdf |archivedate=2014-10-15 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nIn the 2011\u20132012 legislative session, Collins was one of three administrative floor leaders for [[Governor of Georgia|Georgia Governor]] [[Nathan Deal]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://blogs.ajc.com/political-insider-jim-galloway/2012/10/11/martha-zoller-takes-a-temp-job-with-nathan-deal/ | title =Martha Zoller takes a temp job with Nathan Deal | author =Jim Galloway | publisher =''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' | date =October 11, 2012}}</ref> Collins served on the committees for:<ref name=\"athensgop.com\"/>\n* House Appropriations (Secretary)\n* Judiciary Non-Civil\n* Public Safety & Homeland Security\n* Health & Human Services\n* Defense and Veterans Affairs\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===2012 election===\n{{Main article|United States House of Representatives elections in Georgia, 2012}}\nIn 2012, Collins ran for Congress in the redrawn [[Georgia's 9th congressional district|9th congressional district]].  (The district's incumbent, [[Tom Graves]], opted to run in the newly created 14th district, where his home was located.) Collins faced local media personality [[Martha Zoller]] and retired principal Roger Fitzpatrick in the Republican primary. The 9th is the most Republican district in the [[Eastern Time Zone]], with a [[Cook Partisan Voting Index]] of R+27. It was understood that whoever won the Republican primary would be the district's next representative in Congress.\n\nCollins finished first in the primary with 42 percent of the total, but just 700 votes ahead of Zoller. Because neither had a majority, a runoff was held on August 21, 2012, and Collins defeated Zoller in that contest 55 percent to 45 percent.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=773474</ref><ref name=\"103.5\">{{cite web|last=Stephens|first=David|title=Doug Collins Wins Republican Run-Off for Georgia\u2019s 9th Congressional District|url=http://wsgcradio.com/doug-collins-wins-republican-run-off-for-georgias-9th-congressional-district/|publisher=103.5 WSGC|accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref> In the general election, he defeated Democrat Jody Cooley 76 percent to 24 percent.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=753471</ref><ref name=\"Independent Mail\">{{cite web|last=Bynum|first=Ross|title=Doug Collins defeats opponent in Georgia race for U.S. House seat|url=http://www.independentmail.com/news/2012/aug/21/doug-collins-defeats-opponent-georgia-race-us-hous/|work=The Independent Mail (Anderson, SC)|accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Rules Committee]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on the Judiciary]]'''\n** [[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Courts, Intellectual Property and the Internet|Subcommittee on Courts, Intellectual Property and the Internet]]\n** [[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Regulatory Reform, Commercial and Antitrust Law|Subcommittee on Regulatory Reform, Commercial and Antitrust Law]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]'''\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Federal Workforce, U.S. Postal Service and the Census|Subcommittee on Federal Workforce, U.S. Postal Service and the Census]]\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Job Creation and Regulatory Affairs|Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Job Creation and Regulatory Affairs]]\n\n==Defense of Military Chaplains==\nMr. Collins has written letters in defense of military chaplains including [[Joseph Lawhorn]]<ref>{{Cite news|title=Congressman Defends Army Chaplain Under Fire For Exercising Religious Liberty|url=http://dailycaller.com/2015/01/30/army-religious-freedom/|publisher=[[Daily Caller]]|first=Jonah|last=Bennett|date=January 30, 2015|accessdate=April 26, 2015}}</ref> and [[Wes Modder]],<ref>{{Cite news|title=Congressional Members Rally In Support Of Chaplain Modder; Congressman Seeks Answers About How The Navy Obtained Private Information, According To Liberty Institute|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/31/liberty-inst-modder-idUSnPn9RkvGX+93+PRN20150331|publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=March 31, 2015|accessdate=April 26, 2015}}</ref> both of whom have faced opposition for expressing their [[Christian]] beliefs.\n\n==Personal life==\nCollins married his wife, Lisa, in 1988. She is a fifth grade teacher at Mount Vernon Elementary School in [[Gainesville, Georgia]]; where the couple resides with their three children, Jordan, Copelan and Cameron. One of which has spinal bifidia <ref>{{cite web | url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/67851/doug-collins#.UUCkpRyTgV0 | title =Representative Douglas 'Doug' A. Collins's Biography | author =''[[Project Vote Smart]]'' | publisher =votesmart.org | date =March 13, 2013}}</ref> Collins is a practicing [[Southern Baptist Convention|Southern Baptist]], and attends Lakewood Baptist Church.<ref>{{cite web |last=Reiner |first=Anne |title=Southern Baptist contingent in Congress grows |url=http://erlc.com/article/southern-baptist-contingent-in-congress-grows/ |publisher=The Ethics & Religious Liberty Commission of the Southern Baptist Convention |accessdate=18 January 2013 |date=12 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://archive.gainesvilletimes.com/news/stories/20070218/localnews/157004.shtml | title =New kids on the block Every day is a learning process, but Hall's new legislators are settling into their positions | author =Harris Blackwood | publisher =gainesvilletimes.com | date =February 18, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://dougcollins.house.gov/ Congressman Doug Collins] official U.S. House site\n* [http://collinsleads.com/ Doug Collins for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Georgia/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Doug_Collins_%5BR-9%5D|Doug Collins}}\n* {{C-SPAN|dougcollins